******
[1] USA (New York)
Date: Sun 5 Oct 2014
Source: Finger Lake Times [summ., edited]
http://www.fltimes.com/news/article_189b0f74-4c37-11e4-880c-8b4c33053b87.html


An Ontario County resident has a confirmed case of enterovirus D68 [EV-D68], the 1st known instance of the illness in the county.

Barbara Roszak, the county's director of preventive health services, said on Friday [3 Oct 2014] the county public health department was notified of a laboratory-confirmed case in an adult county resident. The person has a history of asthma and is recovering, but the County Director declined to give more detailed information on the patient, including where he or she lives and their age.

Enterovirus D68, which has now been seen in almost every state, has been linked to 4 deaths across the country. The latest fatality was a 10-year-old girl in Rhode Island who died as a result of a bacterial infection associated with EV-D68. According to the national Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, at least 500 people in the US have been sickened so far. Almost all have been children.

According to public health officials, enteroviruses -- which number more than 100 -- are responsible for 10 to 15 million respiratory illnesses each year in the US. The viruses tend to circulate in the summer and fall. "A laboratory-confirmed case of EV-D68 in Ontario County is not unexpected. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention has reported widespread circulation of this illness across the United States and recent cases have been confirmed in Western New York." Roszak said. Enterovirus D68 causes symptoms very similar to a cold or the flu, and can be mild, moderate, or severe. People with enterovirus D68 infection may cause body aches, runny nose, cough, sneezing, and fever. Children and those with asthma are at increased risk for more severe illness. Adults are more likely to have no symptoms or mild symptoms. "Our public health message continues to focus on prevention." [There is no vaccine].

Ontario County Public Health remains in frequent contact with the state Department of Health, area hospitals, urgent care centers, physicians, and schools regarding the illness in the community.

[Byline: Mike Hibbard]

