******
[2] USA (Ohio)
Date: Mon 6 Oct 2014
Source: ThisWeek Community News [summ., edited]
http://www.thisweeknews.com/content/stories/west/news/2014/10/06/enterovirus-is-in-central-ohio-cdc-confirms.html


The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention has confirmed the enterovirus D68 is present in central Ohio and is believed to have sickened many youngsters with upper respiratory illness. Columbus Public Health officials said the test results followed an increase in emergency department, urgent-care visits and hospitalisations. The confirmation comes after Nationwide Children's Hospital sent samples from infected people to the Ohio Department of Health, which then forwarded them to the CDC.

Jose Rodriguez, spokesman for Columbus Public Health, said local health officials were concerned when those with severe respiratory illness who visited emergency rooms jumped from 44 on [14 Aug 2014] to 123 by [9 Sep 2014]. He said that is not a determinant of whether the virus caused the illnesses because regular lab work cannot confirm the existence of the virus. However, the spike did lead medical professionals to believe something out of the ordinary was causing the uptick, he said. Health officials said there's no reason to panic. Most children will recover from the disease within a few days. However, there is potential for severe disease, so children who display wheezing, difficulty breathing or a fever should be checked out by a medical professional, Rodriguez said.

From mid-August to [24 Sep 2014], 220 people in 32 states were confirmed to have respiratory illness caused by EV-D68, said Darlene M Foote, a spokeswoman for the agency. The cases were confirmed by the CDC or state public health labs that notified the agency. All the cases but one were among children. So far, no deaths attributed to EV-D68 infection have been documented, Foote said. Hospitals in Missouri and Illinois have had higher numbers of children with severe respiratory illness caused by EV-D68 than usual for this time of year, she said. Most states likely are affected by respiratory illnesses caused by EV-D68. As investigations progress, the CDC will have a better understanding of whether trends for enterovirus infections are going up or down, she said. Because the disease is caused by a virus, doctors can treat only the symptoms through supportive care. There is no vaccination for enterovirus, Rodriguez said.

[Byline: Gary Seman Jr]

