[3] USA (New Jersey): child fatality
Date: Mon 6 Oct 2014
Source: WTVY-TV, CBS news report [summ., edited]
http://www.wtvy.com/home/headlines/4-Year-Old-Boy-Dies-from-Enterovirus-D-68-278295601.html


A medical examiner says a New Jersey child has died from enterovirus D-68 [virus infection]. It's the 1st such ruling in the country. Even more surprising, the young boy showed none of the cold-like symptoms before his death. Health officials say the death of a 4-year-old boy in New Jersey from enterovirus D-68 is extremely rare. The boy died last month [September 2014] in Hamilton Township after showing no typical signs of the virus. He went to bed with pink eye and never woke up. "The idea that a very rapidly progressive death in one's sleep is surprising but not completely unanticipated," said Dr Anne Schuchat with the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

Enterovirus D-68 [infection] is a respiratory illness that has sickened more than 500 people across the country, many of them children with pre-existing conditions such as asthma. 4 other deaths nationwide have been linked to EV-68 but it's not clear what role the virus played. "Even though enterovirus D68 is quite common this year [2014], it is mainly causing very mild illness and not this most horrific presentation that just occurred," said Dr Schuchat.

Some children with the virus have also experienced paralysis in their limbs, but at this point it's unclear if the polio-like symptoms are related to the virus or caused by something else. Health officials in New Jersey are also keeping an eye on another child in the same school as [the deceased pupil]. He is fighting a respiratory illness. Tests are pending to determine if he has enterovirus [infection].

The CDC recommends frequent hand washing, managing a child's asthma, and getting a flu shot as protective steps.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Kunihiko Iizuka

[The state of New Jersey can be located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2839729,232. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ

According to the CDC from mid-August to 6 Oct 2014, CDC or state public health laboratories have confirmed a total of 594 people in 43 states and the District of Columbia with respiratory illness caused by EV-D68.

The virus, uncommon until recently, typically causes only cold-like symptoms, but some children experience a severe illness with breathing difficulties. Almost all the recent cases involved children, many of them with a history of asthma. The new total reported by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) on 6 Oct 2014 is an increase of 56 from the 538 cases reported 3 Oct 2014. The number of affected states stayed the same, at 43 (http://www.cdc.gov/non-polio-enterovirus/outbreaks/EV-D68-outbreaks.html. The New Jersey case is significant in the abrupt death of the patient.

Last week (week of 29 Sep 2014) the CDC said 4 people who recently died were infected with EV-D68, but it was not clear what role the virus played. Also, Rhode Island officials said last week that a 10-year-old girl who had died of a _Staphylococcus aureus_ infection also was infected with EV-D68. The CDC also said that about half of specimens from patients with severe respiratory illness tested by CDC labs have come back positive for EV-D68. About a third have tested positive for other enteroviruses or rhinoviruses. The CDC and others have been looking into a possible association of the virus with a polio-like illness in children in Colorado and a few other states (http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2014/10/ev-d68-blamed-nj-death-case-count-rises. - Mod.CP]
